[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Such examples may arouse suspicions of being generated by a different mechanism, or appear inconsistent with the remainder of that set of data.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection finds application in many domains including cybersecurity, medicine, machine vision, statistics, neuroscience, law enforcement and financial fraud to name only a few.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Anomalies were initially searched for clear rejection or omission from the data to aid statistical analysis, for example to compute the mean or standard deviation.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] They were also removed to better predictions from models such as linear regression, and more recently their removal aids the performance of machine learning algorithms.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] However, in many applications anomalies themselves are of interest and are the observations most desirous in the entire data set, which need to be identified and separated from noise or irrelevant outliers.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Many attempts have been made in the statistical and computer science communities to define an anomaly.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] The concept of intrusion detection, a critical component of anomaly detection, has evolved significantly over time.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Initially, it was a manual process where system administrators would monitor for unusual activities, such as a vacationing user's account being accessed or unexpected printer activity.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] This approach was not scalable and was soon superseded by the analysis of audit logs and system logs for signs of malicious behavior.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] By the late 1970s and early 1980s, the analysis of these logs was primarily used retrospectively to investigate incidents, as the volume of data made it impractical for real-time monitoring.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] The affordability of digital storage eventually led to audit logs being analyzed online, with specialized programs being developed to sift through the data.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] These programs, however, were typically run during off-peak hours due to their computational intensity.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] The 1990s brought the advent of real-time intrusion detection systems capable of analyzing audit data as it was generated, allowing for immediate detection of and response to attacks.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] This marked a significant shift towards proactive intrusion detection.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] As the field has continued to develop, the focus has shifted to creating solutions that can be efficiently implemented across large and complex network environments, adapting to the ever-growing variety of security threats and the dynamic nature of modern computing infrastructures.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is applicable in a very large number and variety of domains, and is an important subarea of unsupervised machine learning.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] As such it has applications in cyber-security, intrusion detection, fraud detection, fault detection, system health monitoring, event detection in sensor networks, detecting ecosystem disturbances, defect detection in images using machine vision, medical diagnosis and law enforcement.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection was proposed for intrusion detection systems (IDS) by Dorothy Denning in 1986.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection for IDS is normally accomplished with thresholds and statistics, but can also be done with soft computing, and inductive learning.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Types of features proposed by 1999 included profiles of users, workstations, networks, remote hosts, groups of users, and programs based on frequencies, means, variances, covariances, and standard deviations.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] The counterpart of anomaly detection in intrusion detection is misuse detection.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is vital in fintech for fraud prevention.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Preprocessing data to remove anomalies can be an important step in data analysis, and is done for a number of reasons.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Statistics such as the mean and standard deviation are more accurate after the removal of anomalies, and the visualisation of data can also be improved.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] In supervised learning, removing the anomalous data from the dataset often results in a statistically significant increase in accuracy.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection has become increasingly vital in video surveillance to enhance security and safety.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] With the advent of deep learning technologies, methods using Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) and Simple Recurrent Units (SRUs) have shown significant promise in identifying unusual activities or behaviors in video data.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] These models can process and analyze extensive video feeds in real-time, recognizing patterns that deviate from the norm, which may indicate potential security threats or safety violations.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] An important aspect for video surveillance is the development of scalable real-time frameworks.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Such pipelines are required for processing multiple video streams with low computational resources.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] In IT infrastructure management, anomaly detection is crucial for ensuring the smooth operation and reliability of services.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] These are complex systems, composed of many interactive elements and large data quantities, requiring methods to process and reduce this data into a human and machine interpretable format.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Techniques like the IT Infrastructure Library (ITIL) and monitoring frameworks are employed to track and manage system performance and user experience.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Detected anomalies can help identify and pre-empt potential performance degradations or system failures, thus maintaining productivity and business process effectiveness.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is critical for the security and efficiency of Internet of Things (IoT) systems.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] It helps in identifying system failures and security breaches in complex networks of IoT devices.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] The methods must manage real-time data, diverse device types, and scale effectively.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Garg et al. have introduced a multi-stage anomaly detection framework that improves upon traditional methods by incorporating spatial clustering, density-based clustering, and locality-sensitive hashing.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] This tailored approach is designed to better handle the vast and varied nature of IoT data, thereby enhancing security and operational reliability in smart infrastructure and industrial IoT systems.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is crucial in the petroleum industry for monitoring critical machinery.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] A 2015 paper proposed a novel segmentation algorithm using support vector machines to analyze sensor data for real-time anomaly detection.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] In the oil and gas sector, anomaly detection is not just crucial for maintenance and safety, but also for environmental protection.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Aljameel et al. propose an advanced machine learning-based model for detecting minor leaks in oil and gas pipelines, a task traditional methods may miss.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Many anomaly detection techniques have been proposed in literature.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] The performance of methods usually depend on the data sets.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] For example, some may be suited to detecting local outliers, while others global, and methods have little systematic advantages over another when compared across many data sets.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Almost all algorithms also require the setting of non-intuitive parameters critical for performance, and usually unknown before application.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] The size of bins are key to the effectiveness of this technique but must be determined by the implementer.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] A more sophisticated technique uses kernel functions to approximate the distribution of the normal data.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Instances in low probability areas of the distribution are then considered anomalies.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Quantum machine learning approaches have been investigated for anomaly detection on near-term quantum hardware.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Quantum support vector machines (QSVMs) using quantum kernel methods, such as the ZZFeatureMap, have been applied to classification of normal versus anomalous instances by leveraging high-dimensional quantum feature spaces.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Histogram-based Outlier Score (HBOS) uses value histograms and assumes feature independence for fast predictions.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Dynamic networks, such as those representing financial systems, social media interactions, and transportation infrastructure, are subject to constant change, making anomaly detection within them a complex task.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Unlike static graphs, dynamic networks reflect evolving relationships and states, requiring adaptive techniques for anomaly detection.
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] Many of the methods discussed above only yield an anomaly score prediction, which often can be explained to users as the point being in a region of low data density (or relatively low density compared to the neighbor's densities).
[src:anomaly-detection/anomaly-detection] In explainable artificial intelligence, the users demand methods with higher explainability.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] In statistics, an anomaly (a.k.a. outlier) is an observation or event that deviates so much from other events to arouse suspicion it was generated by a different mean.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] For example, the graph in Fig.1 represents ingress traffic to a web server, expressed as the number of requests in 3-hours intervals, for a period of one month.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] It is quite evident by simply looking at the picture that some points (marked with a red circle) are unusually high, to the point of inducing suspect that the web server might have been under attack at that time.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] On the other hand, the flat segment indicated by the red arrow also seems unusual and might possibly be a sign that the server was down during that time period.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] Anomalies in a big dataset may follow very complicated patterns, which are difficult to detect "by eye" in the great majority of cases.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] This is the reason why the field of anomaly detection is well suited for the application of machine learning techniques.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] The most common techniques employed for anomaly detection are based on the construction of a profile of what is "normal": anomalies are reported as those instances in the dataset that do not conform to the normal profile.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] Isolation Forest uses a different approach: instead of trying to build a model of normal instances, it explicitly isolates anomalous points in the dataset.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] The main advantage of this approach is the possibility of exploiting sampling techniques to an extent that is not allowed to the profile-based methods, creating a very fast algorithm with a low memory demand.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] The Isolation Forest (iForest) algorithm was initially proposed by Fei Tony Liu, Kai Ming Ting and Zhi-Hua Zhou in 2008.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] Since anomalies are typically few and very different from the other points in the sample, they must be easier to "isolate" compared to normal points.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] On the basis of this principle, Isolation Forest builds an ensemble of "Isolation Trees" (iTrees) for the data set and marks as anomalies the points that have short average path lengths on the iTrees.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] In 2013 Zhiguo Ding and Minrui Fei proposed a framework based on iForest to resolve the problem of detecting anomalies in streaming data.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] More application of iForest to streaming data are described in papers by Swee Chuan Tan et al., G.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] One of the main problems of the application of iForest to anomaly detection was not with the model itself, but rather in the way the "anomaly score" was computed.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] This problem was highlighted by Sahand Hariri, Matias Carrasco Kind and Robert J.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] Brunner in a 2018 paper, wherein they proposed an improved iForest model named *Extended Isolation Forest* (EIF).
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] In the same paper the authors describe the improvements made to the original model and how they are able to enhance the consistency and reliability of the anomaly score produced for a given data point.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] At the basis of the Isolation Forest algorithm there is the tendency of anomalous instances in a dataset to be easier to separate from the rest of the sample (isolate), compared to normal points.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] In order to isolate a data point the algorithm recursively generates partitions on the sample by randomly selecting an attribute and then randomly selecting a split value for the attribute, between the minimum and maximum values allowed for that attribute.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] An example of random partitioning in a 2D dataset of normally distributed points is given in Fig.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] 3 for a point that's more likely to be an anomaly.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] It is apparent from the pictures how anomalies require fewer random partitions to be isolated, compared to normal points.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] From a mathematical point of view, recursive partitioning can be represented by a tree structure named *Isolation Tree*, while the number of partitions required to isolate a point can be interpreted as the length of the path, within the tree, to reach a terminating node starting from the root.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] For example, the path length of point xi in Fig.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] 2 is greater than the path length of xj in Fig.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] More formally, let X = { x1, ..., xn } be a set of d-dimensional points and X' ⊂ X a subset of X.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] 2. a test at node T consists of an attribute q and a split value p such that the test q < p determines the traversal of a data point to either Tl or Tr.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] In order to build an iTree, the algorithm recursively divides X' by randomly selecting an attribute q and a split value p, until either (i) the node has only one instance or (ii) all data at the node have the same values.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] When the iTree is fully grown, each point in X is isolated at one of the external nodes.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] Intuitively, the anomalous points are those (easier to isolate, hence) with the smaller *path length* in the tree, where the path length h(xi) of point $x_{i}\in X$ is defined as the number of edges xi traverses from the root node to get to an external node.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] A probabilistic explanation of iTree is provided in the iForest original paper.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] Once all the instances in the test set have been assigned an anomaly score, it is possible to mark as "anomaly" any point whose score is greater than a predefined threshold, which depends on the domain the analysis is being applied to.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] The algorithm for computing the anomaly score of a data point is based on the observation that the structure of iTrees is equivalent to that of Binary Search Trees (BST): a termination to an external node of the iTree corresponds to an unsuccessful search in the BST.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] where m is the testing data size, m is the size of the sample set and H is the harmonic number, which can be estimated by $H(i)=ln(i)+\gamma$ , where $\gamma =0.5772156649$ is the Euler-Mascheroni constant.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] where E(h(x)) is the average value of h(x) from a collection of iTrees.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] As described in the previous sections, the Isolation Forest algorithm performs very well from both the computational and the memory consumption points of view.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] The main problem with the original algorithm is that the way the branching of trees takes place introduce a bias, which is likely to reduce the reliability of the anomaly scores for ranking the data.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] This is the main motivation behind the introduction of the *Extended Isolation Forest* (EIF) algorithm by Hariri et al.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] In order to understand why the original Isolation Forest suffers from that bias, the authors provide a practical example based on a random dataset taken from a 2-D normal distribution with zero mean and covariance given by the identity matrix.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] An example of such a dataset is shown in Fig.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] It is easy to understand by looking at the picture that points falling close to (0, 0) are likely to be normal points, while a point that lies far away from (0, 0) is likely to be anomalous.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] As a consequence, the anomaly score of a point should increase with an almost circular and symmetric pattern as the point move radially outward the "centre" of the distribution.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] This is not the case in practice as the authors demonstrate by generating the anomaly score map produced for the distribution by the Isolation Forest algorithm.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] Although the anomaly scores correctly increase as the points move radially outward, they also generate rectangular regions of lower anomaly score in the x and y directions, compared to other points that fall roughly at the same radial distance from the centre.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] It is possible to demonstrate that these unexpected rectangular regions in the anomaly score map are indeed an artifact introduced by the algorithm and are mainly due to the fact that the decision boundaries of Isolation Forest are limited to be either vertical or horizontal (see Fig.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] This is the reason why in their paper, Hariri et al. propose to improve the original Isolation Forest in the following way: rather than selecting a random feature and value within the range of data, they select a branch cut that has a random "slope".
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] An example of random partitioning with EIF is shown in Fig.
[src:anomaly-detection/isolation-forest] The authors show how the new approach is able to overcome the limits of the original Isolation Forest, eventually leading to an improved anomaly score map.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] In anomaly detection, the **local outlier factor** (**LOF**) is an algorithm proposed by Markus M.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] Ng and Jörg Sander in 2000 for finding anomalous data points by measuring the local deviation of a given data point with respect to its neighbours.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] LOF shares some concepts with DBSCAN and OPTICS such as the concepts of "core distance" and "reachability distance", which are used for local density estimation.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] The local outlier factor is based on a concept of a local density, where locality is given by *k* nearest neighbors, whose distance is used to estimate the density.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] By comparing the local density of an object to the local densities of its neighbors, one can identify regions of similar density, and points that have a substantially lower density than their neighbors.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] The local density is estimated by the typical distance at which a point can be "reached" from its neighbors.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] The definition of "reachability distance" used in LOF is an additional measure to produce more stable results within clusters.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] The "reachability distance" used by LOF has some subtle details that are often found incorrect in secondary sources, e.g., in the textbook of Ethem Alpaydin.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] Let $k{\text{-distance}}(A)$ be the distance of the object *A* to the *k*-th nearest neighbor.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] Note that the set of the *k* nearest neighbors includes all objects at this distance, which can in the case of a "tie" be more than *k* objects.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] We denote the set of *k* nearest neighbors as $N_{k}(A)$ .
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] In words, the *reachability distance* of an object *A* *from* *B* is the true distance between the two objects, but at least the $k{\text{-distance}}$ of *B*.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] Objects that belong to the *k* nearest neighbors of *B* (the "core" of *B*, see DBSCAN cluster analysis) are considered to be equally distant.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] The reason for this is to reduce the statistical fluctuations between all points *A* close to *B*, where increasing the value for *k* increases the smoothing effect.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] Note that this is not a distance in the mathematical definition, since it is not symmetric.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] which is the inverse of the average reachability distance of the object *A* *from* its neighbors.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] Note that it is not the average reachability of the neighbors from *A* (which by definition would be the $k{\text{-distance}}(A)$ ), but the distance at which *A* can be "reached" *from* its neighbors.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] With duplicate points, this value can become infinite.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] which is the *average local reachability density of the neighbors* divided by the object's own local reachability density.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] A value of approximately 1 indicates that the object is comparable to its neighbors (and thus not an outlier).
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] A value below 1 indicates a denser region (which would be an inlier), while values significantly larger than 1 indicate outliers.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] Due to the local approach, LOF is able to identify outliers in a data set that would not be outliers in another area of the data set.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] For example, a point at a "small" distance to a very dense cluster is an outlier, while a point within a sparse cluster might exhibit similar distances to its neighbors.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] While the geometric intuition of LOF is only applicable to low-dimensional vector spaces, the algorithm can be applied in any context a dissimilarity function can be defined.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] It has experimentally been shown to work very well in numerous setups, often outperforming the competitors, for example in network intrusion detection and on processed classification benchmark data.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] The LOF family of methods can be easily generalized and then applied to various other problems, such as detecting outliers in geographic data, video streams or authorship networks.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] The resulting values are quotient-values and hard to interpret.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] A value of 1 or even less indicates a clear inlier, but there is no clear rule for when a point is an outlier.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] In one data set, a value of 1.1 may already be an outlier, in another dataset and parameterization (with strong local fluctuations) a value of 2 could still be an inlier.
[src:anomaly-detection/local-outlier-factor] These differences can also occur within a dataset due to the locality of the method.
[src:anomaly-detection/novelty-detection] The principle is long known in neurophysiology, with roots in the orienting response research by E.
[src:anomaly-detection/novelty-detection] The reverse phenomenon is habituation, i.e., the phenomenon that known patterns yield a less marked response.
[src:anomaly-detection/novelty-detection] Early neural modeling attempts were by Yehuda Salu.
[src:anomaly-detection/novelty-detection] An increasing body of knowledge has been collected concerning the corresponding mechanisms in the brain.
[src:anomaly-detection/novelty-detection] In technology, the principle became important for radar detection methods during the Cold War, where unusual aircraft-reflection patterns could indicate an attack by a new type of aircraft.
[src:anomaly-detection/novelty-detection] Today, the phenomenon plays an important role in machine learning and data science, where the corresponding methods are known as anomaly detection or outlier detection.
[src:anomaly-detection/novelty-detection] An extensive methodological overview is given by Markou and Singh.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] In statistics, an **outlier** is a data point that differs significantly from other observations.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] An outlier may be due to a variability in the measurement, an indication of novel data, or it may be the result of experimental error; the latter are sometimes excluded from the data set.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] An outlier can be an indication of exciting possibility, but can also cause serious problems in statistical analyses.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Outliers can occur by chance in any distribution, but they can indicate novel behaviour or structures in the data-set, measurement error, or that the population has a heavy-tailed distribution.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] A frequent cause of outliers is a mixture of two distributions, which may be two distinct sub-populations, or may indicate 'correct trial' versus 'measurement error'; this is modeled by a mixture model.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] In most larger samplings of data, some data points will be further away from the sample mean than what is deemed reasonable.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] This can be due to incidental systematic error or flaws in the theory that generated an assumed family of probability distributions, or it may be that some observations are far from the center of the data.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Outlier points can therefore indicate faulty data, erroneous procedures, or areas where a certain theory might not be valid.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] However, in large samples, a small number of outliers is to be expected (and not due to any anomalous condition).
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Outliers, being the most extreme observations, may include the sample maximum or sample minimum, or both, depending on whether they are extremely high or low.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] However, the sample maximum and minimum are not always outliers because they may not be unusually far from other observations.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Naive interpretation of statistics derived from data sets that include outliers may be misleading.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] For example, if one is calculating the average temperature of 10 objects in a room, and nine of them are between 20 and 25 degrees Celsius, but an oven is at 175 °C, the median of the data will be between 20 and 25 °C but the mean temperature will be between 35.5 and 40 °C.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] In this case, the median better reflects the temperature of a randomly sampled object (but not the temperature in the room) than the mean; naively interpreting the mean as "a typical sample", equivalent to the median, is incorrect.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] As illustrated in this case, outliers may indicate data points that belong to a different population than the rest of the sample set.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Estimators capable of coping with outliers are said to be robust: the median is a robust statistic of central tendency, while the mean is not.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] In the case of normally distributed data, the three sigma rule means that roughly 1 in 22 observations will differ by twice the standard deviation or more from the mean, and 1 in 370 will deviate by three times the standard deviation.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] If the sample size is only 100, however, just three such outliers are already reason for concern, being more than 11 times the expected number.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Thus if one takes a normal distribution with cutoff 3 standard deviations from the mean, *p* is approximately 0.3%, and thus for 1000 trials one can approximate the number of samples whose deviation exceeds 3 sigmas by a Poisson distribution with λ = 3.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Outliers can have many anomalous causes.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] A physical apparatus for taking measurements may have suffered a transient malfunction.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] There may have been an error in data transmission or transcription.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Outliers arise due to changes in system behaviour, fraudulent behaviour, human error, instrument error or simply through natural deviations in populations.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] A sample may have been contaminated with elements from outside the population being examined.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Alternatively, an outlier could be the result of a flaw in the assumed theory, calling for further investigation by the researcher.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Additionally, the pathological appearance of outliers of a certain form appears in a variety of datasets, indicating that the causative mechanism for the data might differ at the extreme end (King effect).
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] There is no rigid mathematical definition of what constitutes an outlier; determining whether or not an observation is an outlier is ultimately a subjective exercise.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] There are various methods of outlier detection, some of which are treated as synonymous with novelty detection.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Some are graphical such as normal probability plots.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Other methods flag observations based on measures such as the interquartile range.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] John Tukey proposed this test, where $k=1.5$ indicates an "outlier", and $k=3$ indicates data that is "far out".
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] In various domains such as, but not limited to, statistics, signal processing, finance, econometrics, manufacturing, networking and data mining, the task of *anomaly detection* may take other approaches.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Some of these may be distance-based and density-based such as Local Outlier Factor (LOF).
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Some approaches may use the distance to the k-nearest neighbors to label observations as outliers or non-outliers.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] The modified Thompson Tau test is a method used to determine if an outlier exists in a data set.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] The strength of this method lies in the fact that it takes into account a data set's standard deviation, average and provides a statistically determined rejection zone; thus providing an objective method to determine if a data point is an outlier.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] How it works: First, a data set's average is determined.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Next the absolute deviation between each data point and the average are determined.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] where $\scriptstyle {t_{\alpha /2}}$ is the critical value from the Student t distribution with *n*-2 degrees of freedom, *n* is the sample size, and s is the sample standard deviation.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] To determine if a value is an outlier: Calculate $\scriptstyle \delta =|(X-mean(X))/s|$ .
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] If *δ* > Rejection Region, the data point is an outlier.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] If *δ* ≤ Rejection Region, the data point is not an outlier.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] The modified Thompson Tau test is used to find one outlier at a time (largest value of *δ* is removed if it is an outlier).
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Meaning, if a data point is found to be an outlier, it is removed from the data set and the test is applied again with a new average and rejection region.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] This process is continued until no outliers remain in a data set.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Some work has also examined outliers for nominal (or categorical) data.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] In the context of a set of examples (or instances) in a data set, instance hardness measures the probability that an instance will be misclassified ( $1-p(y|x)$ where y is the assigned class label and x represent the input attribute value for an instance in the training set t).
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Practically, this formulation is unfeasible as H is potentially infinite and calculating $p(h|t)$ is unknown for many algorithms.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] where $g_{j}(t,\alpha )$ is the hypothesis induced by learning algorithm $g_{j}$ trained on training set t with hyperparameters $\alpha$ .
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Instance hardness provides a continuous value for determining if an instance is an outlier instance.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] The choice of how to deal with an outlier should depend on the cause.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Some estimators are highly sensitive to outliers, notably estimation of covariance matrices.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Even when a normal distribution model is appropriate to the data being analyzed, outliers are expected for large sample sizes and should not automatically be discarded if that is the case.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Instead, one should use a method that is robust to outliers to model or analyze data with naturally occurring outliers.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] When deciding whether to remove an outlier, the cause has to be considered.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] As mentioned earlier, if the outlier's origin can be attributed to an experimental error, or if it can be otherwise determined that the outlying data point is erroneous, it is generally recommended to remove it.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] However, it is more desirable to correct the erroneous value, if possible.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Removing a data point solely because it is an outlier, on the other hand, is a controversial practice, often frowned upon by many scientists and science instructors, as it typically invalidates statistical results.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] While mathematical criteria provide an objective and quantitative method for data rejection, they do not make the practice more scientifically or methodologically sound, especially in small sets or where a normal distribution cannot be assumed.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Rejection of outliers is more acceptable in areas of practice where the underlying model of the process being measured and the usual distribution of measurement error are confidently known.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] The two common approaches to exclude outliers are truncation (or trimming) and Winsorising.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Trimming discards the outliers whereas Winsorising replaces the outliers with the nearest "nonsuspect" data.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Exclusion can also be a consequence of the measurement process, such as when an experiment is not entirely capable of measuring such extreme values, resulting in censored data.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] In regression problems, an alternative approach may be to only exclude points which exhibit a large degree of influence on the estimated coefficients, using a measure such as Cook's distance.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] If a data point (or points) is excluded from the data analysis, this should be clearly stated on any subsequent report.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] The possibility should be considered that the underlying distribution of the data is not approximately normal, having "fat tails".
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] For instance, when sampling from a Cauchy distribution, the sample variance increases with the sample size, the sample mean fails to converge as the sample size increases, and outliers are expected at far larger rates than for a normal distribution.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Even a slight difference in the fatness of the tails can make a large difference in the expected number of extreme values.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] A set membership approach considers that the uncertainty corresponding to the *i*th measurement of an unknown random vector *x* is represented by a set *X*i (instead of a probability density function).
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] If no outliers occur, *x* should belong to the intersection of all *X*i's.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] When outliers occur, this intersection could be empty, and we should relax a small number of the sets *X*i (as small as possible) in order to avoid any inconsistency.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] This can be done using the notion of *q*-relaxed intersection.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] As illustrated by the figure, the *q*-relaxed intersection corresponds to the set of all *x* which belong to all sets except *q* of them.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Sets *X*i that do not intersect the *q*-relaxed intersection could be suspected to be outliers.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] In cases where the cause of the outliers is known, it may be possible to incorporate this effect into the model structure, for example by using a hierarchical Bayes model, or a mixture model.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] In cluster analysis, outliers can greatly distort the results.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Thus, the handling of outliers has been an issue of much discussion.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] Cluster analysis relies heavily on distance measures.
[src:anomaly-detection/outlier] It has been suggested that Manhattan distance, due to the lack of squaring disproportionately large difference values, is likely to handle outliers better than Euclidean distance.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] In machine learning, **support vector machines** (**SVMs**, also **support vector networks**) are supervised max-margin models with associated learning algorithms that analyze data for classification and regression analysis.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Developed at AT&T Bell Laboratories, SVMs are one of the most studied models, being based on statistical learning frameworks of VC theory proposed by Vapnik (1982, 1995) and Chervonenkis (1974).
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Thus, SVMs use the kernel trick to implicitly map their inputs into high-dimensional feature spaces, where linear classification can be performed.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Being max-margin models, SVMs are resilient to noisy data (e.g., misclassified examples).
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] SVMs can also be used for regression tasks, where the objective becomes $\epsilon$ -sensitive.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The support vector clustering algorithm, created by Hava Siegelmann and Vladimir Vapnik, applies the statistics of support vectors, developed in the support vector machines algorithm, to categorize unlabeled data.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] These data sets require unsupervised learning approaches, which attempt to find natural clustering of the data into groups, and then to map new data according to these clusters.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The popularity of SVMs is likely due to their amenability to theoretical analysis, and their flexibility in being applied to a wide variety of tasks, including structured prediction problems.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] It is not clear that SVMs have better predictive performance than other linear models, such as logistic regression and linear regression.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Classifying data is a common task in machine learning.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Suppose some given data points each belong to one of two classes, and the goal is to decide which class a *new* data point will be in.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] In the case of support vector machines, a data point is viewed as a p -dimensional vector (a list of p numbers), and we want to know whether we can separate such points with a $(p-1)$ -dimensional hyperplane.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] There are many hyperplanes that might classify the data.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] One reasonable choice as the best hyperplane is the one that represents the largest separation, or margin, between the two classes.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] So we choose the hyperplane so that the distance from it to the nearest data point on each side is maximized.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] If such a hyperplane exists, it is known as the *maximum-margin hyperplane* and the linear classifier it defines is known as a *maximum-margin classifier*; or equivalently, the *perceptron of optimal stability*.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] More formally, a support vector machine constructs a hyperplane or set of hyperplanes in a high or infinite-dimensional space, which can be used for classification, regression, or other tasks like outlier detection.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Intuitively, a good separation is achieved by the hyperplane that has the largest distance to the nearest training-data point of any class (so-called functional margin), since in general the larger the margin, the lower the generalization error of the classifier.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] A lower generalization error means that the implementer is less likely to experience overfitting.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Whereas the original problem may be stated in a finite-dimensional space, it often happens that the sets to discriminate are not linearly separable in that space.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] For this reason, it was proposed that the original finite-dimensional space be mapped into a much higher-dimensional space, presumably making the separation easier in that space.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The hyperplanes in the higher-dimensional space are defined as the set of points whose dot product with a vector in that space is constant, where such a set of vectors is an orthogonal (and thus minimal) set of vectors that defines a hyperplane.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The vectors defining the hyperplanes can be chosen to be linear combinations with parameters $\alpha _{i}$ of images of feature vectors $x_{i}$ that occur in the data base.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] In this way, the sum of kernels above can be used to measure the relative nearness of each test point to the data points originating in one or the other of the sets to be discriminated.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Note the fact that the set of points x mapped into any hyperplane can be quite convoluted as a result, allowing much more complex discrimination between sets that are not convex at all in the original space.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The original SVM algorithm was invented by Vladimir N.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] In 1992, Bernhard Boser, Isabelle Guyon and Vladimir Vapnik suggested a way to create nonlinear classifiers by applying the kernel trick to maximum-margin hyperplanes.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The "soft margin" incarnation, as is commonly used in software packages, was proposed by Corinna Cortes and Vapnik in 1993 and published in 1995.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] We are given a training dataset of n points of the form $(\mathbf {x} _{1},y_{1}),\ldots ,(\mathbf {x} _{n},y_{n}),$ where the $y_{i}$ are either 1 or −1, each indicating the class to which the point $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ belongs.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Each $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ is a p -dimensional real vector.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Any hyperplane can be written as the set of points $\mathbf {x}$ satisfying $\mathbf {w} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {x} -b=0,$ where $\mathbf {w}$ is the (not necessarily normalized) normal vector to the hyperplane.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] This is much like Hesse normal form, except that $\mathbf {w}$ is not necessarily a unit vector.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The parameter ${\tfrac {b}{\|\mathbf {w} \|}}$ determines the offset of the hyperplane from the origin along the normal vector $\mathbf {w}$ .
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] If the training data is linearly separable, we can select two parallel hyperplanes that separate the two classes of data, so that the distance between them is as large as possible.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The region bounded by these two hyperplanes is called the "margin", and the maximum-margin hyperplane is the hyperplane that lies halfway between them.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] (anything on or below this boundary is of the other class, with label −1).
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Geometrically, the distance between these two hyperplanes is ${\tfrac {2}{\|\mathbf {w} \|}}$ , so to maximize the distance between the planes we want to minimize $\|\mathbf {w} \|$ .
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The distance is computed using the distance from a point to a plane equation.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The $\mathbf {w}$ and b that solve this problem determine the final classifier, $\mathbf {x} \mapsto \operatorname {sgn}(\mathbf {w} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {x} -b)$ , where $\operatorname {sgn}(\cdot )$ is the sign function.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] An important consequence of this geometric description is that the max-margin hyperplane is completely determined by those $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ that lie nearest to it (explained below).
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] These $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ are called *support vectors*.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] This function is zero if the constraint in **(1)** is satisfied, in other words, if $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ lies on the correct side of the margin.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] For data on the wrong side of the margin, the function's value is proportional to the distance from the margin.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] where the parameter $C>0$ determines the trade-off between increasing the margin size and ensuring that the $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ lie on the correct side of the margin (Note we can add a weight to either term in the equation above).
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Thus, for large values of C , it will behave similar to the hard-margin SVM, if the input data are linearly classifiable, but will still learn if a classification rule is viable or not.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The original maximum-margin hyperplane algorithm proposed by Vapnik in 1963 constructed a linear classifier.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] However, in 1992, Bernhard Boser, Isabelle Guyon and Vladimir Vapnik suggested a way to create nonlinear classifiers by applying the kernel trick (originally proposed by Aizerman et al.) to maximum-margin hyperplanes.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The kernel trick, where dot products are replaced by kernels, is easily derived in the dual representation of the SVM problem.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] This allows the algorithm to fit the maximum-margin hyperplane in a transformed feature space.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The transformation may be nonlinear and the transformed space high-dimensional; although the classifier is a hyperplane in the transformed feature space, it may be nonlinear in the original input space.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] It is noteworthy that working in a higher-dimensional feature space increases the generalization error of support vector machines, although given enough samples the algorithm still performs well.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The kernel is related to the transform $\varphi (\mathbf {x} _{i})$ by the equation $k(\mathbf {x} _{i},\mathbf {x} _{j})=\varphi (\mathbf {x} _{i})\cdot \varphi (\mathbf {x} _{j})$ .
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The value **w** is also in the transformed space, with ${\textstyle \mathbf {w} =\sum _{i}\alpha _{i}y_{i}\varphi (\mathbf {x} _{i})}$ .
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Dot products with **w** for classification can again be computed by the kernel trick, i.e. ${\textstyle \mathbf {w} \cdot \varphi (\mathbf {x} )=\sum _{i}\alpha _{i}y_{i}k(\mathbf {x} _{i},\mathbf {x} )}$ .
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] We focus on the soft-margin classifier since, as noted above, choosing a sufficiently small value for $\lambda$ yields the hard-margin classifier for linearly classifiable input data.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The classical approach, which involves reducing **(2)** to a quadratic programming problem, is detailed below.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Then, more recent approaches such as sub-gradient descent and coordinate descent will be discussed.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Minimizing **(2)** can be rewritten as a constrained optimization problem with a differentiable objective function in the following way.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Since the dual maximization problem is a quadratic function of the $c_{i}$ subject to linear constraints, it is efficiently solvable by quadratic programming algorithms.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Moreover, $c_{i}=0$ exactly when $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ lies on the correct side of the margin, and $0<c_{i}<(2n\lambda )^{-1}$ when $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ lies on the margin's boundary.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] It follows that $\mathbf {w}$ can be written as a linear combination of the support vectors.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The coefficients $c_{i}$ can be solved for using quadratic programming, as before.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Recent algorithms for finding the SVM classifier include sub-gradient descent and coordinate descent.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Both techniques have proven to offer significant advantages over the traditional approach when dealing with large, sparse datasets—sub-gradient methods are especially efficient when there are many training examples, and coordinate descent when the dimension of the feature space is high.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Note that f is a convex function of $\mathbf {w}$ and b .
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] As such, traditional gradient descent (or SGD) methods can be adapted, where instead of taking a step in the direction of the function's gradient, a step is taken in the direction of a vector selected from the function's sub-gradient.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] This approach has the advantage that, for certain implementations, the number of iterations does not scale with n , the number of data points.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] For each $i\in \{1,\,\ldots ,\,n\}$ , iteratively, the coefficient $c_{i}$ is adjusted in the direction of $\partial f/\partial c_{i}$ .
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Then, the resulting vector of coefficients $(c_{1}',\,\ldots ,\,c_{n}')$ is projected onto the nearest vector of coefficients that satisfies the given constraints.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] (Typically Euclidean distances are used.) The process is then repeated until a near-optimal vector of coefficients is obtained.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The resulting algorithm is extremely fast in practice, although few performance guarantees have been proven.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The soft-margin support vector machine described above is an example of an empirical risk minimization (ERM) algorithm for the *hinge loss*.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Seen this way, support vector machines belong to a natural class of algorithms for statistical inference, and many of its unique features are due to the behavior of the hinge loss.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] This perspective can provide further insight into how and why SVMs work, and allow us to better analyze their statistical properties.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] In supervised learning, one is given a set of training examples $X_{1}\ldots X_{n}$ with labels $y_{1}\ldots y_{n}$ , and wishes to predict $y_{n+1}$ given $X_{n+1}$ .
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] To do so one forms a hypothesis, f , such that $f(X_{n+1})$ is a "good" approximation of $y_{n+1}$ .
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] A "good" approximation is usually defined with the help of a *loss function,* $\ell (y,z)$ , which characterizes how bad z is as a prediction of y .
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] In most cases, we don't know the joint distribution of $X_{n+1},\,y_{n+1}$ outright.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] This approach is called *empirical risk minimization,* or ERM.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] In order for the minimization problem to have a well-defined solution, we have to place constraints on the set ${\mathcal {H}}$ of hypotheses being considered.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] If ${\mathcal {H}}$ is a normed space (as is the case for SVM), a particularly effective technique is to consider only those hypotheses f for which $\lVert f\rVert _{\mathcal {H}}<k$ .
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] More generally, ${\mathcal {R}}(f)$ can be some measure of the complexity of the hypothesis f , so that simpler hypotheses are preferred.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] From this perspective, SVM is closely related to other fundamental classification algorithms such as regularized least-squares and logistic regression.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The difference between the hinge loss and these other loss functions is best stated in terms of *target functions -* the function that minimizes expected risk for a given pair of random variables $X,\,y$ .
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] In particular, let $y_{x}$ denote y conditional on the event that $X=x$ .
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] For the square-loss, the target function is the conditional expectation function, $f_{sq}(x)=\mathbb {E} \left[y_{x}\right]$ ; For the logistic loss, it's the logit function, $f_{\log }(x)=\ln \left(p_{x}/({1-p_{x}})\right)$ .
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] While both of these target functions yield the correct classifier, as $\operatorname {sgn}(f_{sq})=\operatorname {sgn}(f_{\log })=f^{*}$ , they give us more information than we need.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] In fact, they give us enough information to completely describe the distribution of $y_{x}$ .
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] On the other hand, one can check that the target function for the hinge loss is *exactly* $f^{*}$ .
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Thus, in a sufficiently rich hypothesis space—or equivalently, for an appropriately chosen kernel—the SVM classifier will converge to the simplest function (in terms of ${\mathcal {R}}$ ) that correctly classifies the data.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] This extends the geometric interpretation of SVM—for linear classification, the empirical risk is minimized by any function whose margins lie between the support vectors, and the simplest of these is the max-margin classifier.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] SVMs belong to a family of generalized linear classifiers and can be interpreted as an extension of the perceptron.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] They can also be considered a special case of Tikhonov regularization.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] A special property is that they simultaneously minimize the empirical *classification error* and maximize the *geometric margin*; hence they are also known as **maximum margin classifiers**.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] A comparison of the SVM to other classifiers has been made by Meyer, Leisch and Hornik.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The effectiveness of SVM depends on the selection of kernel, the kernel's parameters, and soft margin parameter $\lambda$ .
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] A common choice is a Gaussian kernel, which has a single parameter *$\gamma$*.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Typically, each combination of parameter choices is checked using cross validation, and the parameters with best cross-validation accuracy are picked.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Alternatively, recent work in Bayesian optimization can be used to select $\lambda$ and *$\gamma$* , often requiring the evaluation of far fewer parameter combinations than grid search.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The final model, which is used for testing and for classifying new data, is then trained on the whole training set using the selected parameters.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Multiclass SVM aims to assign labels to instances by using support vector machines, where the labels are drawn from a finite set of several elements.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The dominant approach for doing so is to reduce the single multiclass problem into multiple binary classification problems.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Crammer and Singer proposed a multiclass SVM method which casts the multiclass classification problem into a single optimization problem, rather than decomposing it into multiple binary classification problems.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] See also Lee, Lin and Wahba and Van den Burg and Groenen.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Transductive support vector machines extend SVMs in that they could also treat partially labeled data in semi-supervised learning by following the principles of transduction.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Transductive support vector machines were introduced by Vladimir N.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Structured support-vector machine is an extension of the traditional SVM model.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] While the SVM model is primarily designed for binary classification, multiclass classification, and regression tasks, structured SVM broadens its application to handle general structured output labels, for example parse trees, classification with taxonomies, sequence alignment and many more.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] A version of SVM for regression was proposed in 1996 by Vladimir N.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] This method is called support vector regression (SVR).
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The model produced by support vector classification (as described above) depends only on a subset of the training data, because the cost function for building the model does not care about training points that lie beyond the margin.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Analogously, the model produced by SVR depends only on a subset of the training data, because the cost function for building the model ignores any training data close to the model prediction.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Another SVM version known as least-squares support vector machine (LS-SVM) has been proposed by Suykens and Vandewalle.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] where $x_{i}$ is a training sample with target value $y_{i}$ .
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The inner product plus intercept $\langle w,x_{i}\rangle +b$ is the prediction for that sample, and $\varepsilon$ is a free parameter that serves as a threshold: all predictions have to be within an $\varepsilon$ range of the true predictions.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Slack variables are usually added into the above to allow for errors and to allow approximation in the case the above problem is infeasible.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] In 2011 it was shown by Polson and Scott that the SVM admits a Bayesian interpretation through the technique of data augmentation.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] In this approach the SVM is viewed as a graphical model (where the parameters are connected via probability distributions).
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] This extended view allows the application of Bayesian techniques to SVMs, such as flexible feature modeling, automatic hyperparameter tuning, and predictive uncertainty quantification.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] In 2017, a scalable version of the Bayesian SVM was developed by Florian Wenzel, enabling the application of Bayesian SVMs to big data.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Florian Wenzel developed two different versions, a variational inference (VI) scheme for the Bayesian kernel support vector machine (SVM) and a stochastic version (SVI) for the linear Bayesian SVM.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The parameters of the maximum-margin hyperplane are derived by solving the optimization.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] There exist several specialized algorithms for quickly solving the quadratic programming (QP) problem that arises from SVMs, mostly relying on heuristics for breaking the problem down into smaller, more manageable chunks.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Another approach is to use an interior-point method that uses Newton-like iterations to find a solution of the Karush–Kuhn–Tucker conditions of the primal and dual problems.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Instead of solving a sequence of broken-down problems, this approach directly solves the problem altogether.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] To avoid solving a linear system involving the large kernel matrix, a low-rank approximation to the matrix is often used in the kernel trick.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Another common method is Platt's sequential minimal optimization (SMO) algorithm, which breaks the problem down into 2-dimensional sub-problems that are solved analytically, eliminating the need for a numerical optimization algorithm and matrix storage.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] This algorithm is conceptually simple, easy to implement, generally faster, and has better scaling properties for difficult SVM problems.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The special case of linear support vector machines can be solved more efficiently by the same kind of algorithms used to optimize its close cousin, logistic regression; this class of algorithms includes sub-gradient descent (e.g., PEGASOS) and coordinate descent (e.g., LIBLINEAR).
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] LIBLINEAR has some attractive training-time properties.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Each convergence iteration takes time linear in the time taken to read the train data, and the iterations also have a Q-linear convergence property, making the algorithm extremely fast.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] The general kernel SVMs can also be solved more efficiently using sub-gradient descent (e.g.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] P-packSVM), especially when parallelization is allowed.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Kernel SVMs are available in many machine-learning toolkits, including LIBSVM, MATLAB, SAS, SVMlight, kernlab, scikit-learn, Shogun, Weka, Shark, JKernelMachines, OpenCV and others.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Preprocessing of data (standardization) is highly recommended to enhance accuracy of classification.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] There are a few methods of standardization, such as min-max, normalization by decimal scaling, Z-score.
[src:anomaly-detection/support-vector-machine] Subtraction of mean and division by variance of each feature is usually used for SVM.
